ext_heat_cope_comments:
To cope with extreme heat:

- Stay hydrated and wear light clothing.
- Use fans or air conditioning, or visit air-conditioned places.
- Close curtains to block sunlight.
- Take cool showers or use cold compresses.
- Limit outdoor activities during peak heat.
- Avoid heavy meals and alcohol.
- Monitor vulnerable individuals, like the elderly and children.

These steps help prevent heat-related health issues.
ext_cold_cope_comments:
To cope with extreme cold:

- Insulate your home to keep heat in.
- Eat high-calorie foods for warmth.
- Stay dry and wear moisture-wicking clothes.
- Keep moving to generate heat.
- Drink warm beverages.
- Protect extremities with hats, gloves, and thick socks.

These steps help prevent frostbite and hypothermia.
comments:
To prepare for severe disruptions or extreme events, communities should:

- Develop emergency plans and ensure everyone knows them.
- Create communication networks for quick alerts.
- Stock essential supplies like food, water, and medical kits.
- Strengthen local infrastructure to withstand events.
- Encourage resilience training and disaster drills.

These measures improve community readiness for unexpected crises.

Normally spend more time indoors during extreme heat in Phoenix Arizona.  However I do find if I need to do yard work, if I start early in the morning and limit time inside air-conditioned home, and take frequent water breaks in shade - the heat is not as bad versus if I try to start yard project at noon.  Hydration and proper clothes (long sleeve thin loose fitting cotton shirts and hat that covers head and long thin cotton loose fitting pants allow me to work outside in yard - as well as taking breaks in the shade and pacing work - attitude is big as well - meaning enjoy the time - enjoy the birds in the trees watching - I am sure the bird think yard work is crazy.
ext_powerout_cope_comments: I have some candles, an outdoor gas grill and gasoline powered generator that will run refrigerator ready for a longer term, neighborhood-wide power outage to support a 5 day time frame which should be enough time to calmly determine the next action(s) that I would need to take to support family and any friends who wanted to stay over.  If longer term power outage, and if roads were accessible, then would more than likely drive to ranch in northern Arizona which is situated in the center of the national forest, closest neighbor 7 miles away that has 50'well run by wind (water supply) with drinking water storage tanks as well as solar powered generator for any electrical needs as well as supply or candles and gas tanks for heating homestead and cooking purposes. So that pretty much is more than likely what I would do to cope and of course any family or friend would be invite either place until issue was resolved.

ext_cold_cope_comments: Honestly, I've lived in Central Minnesota my whole life. Extreme cold doesn't usually stop us from going to work. Usually if your car won't start, someone that has a heated garage will come get you, whether it's family, a friend, or a coworker. Sometimes locals do stock up on gas or food so they don't have to go out and about in the worst cold temps. But it's all pretty standard here. We watch the news, employers keep workers posted at these times about their plans, and we usually plan accordingly. I even stayed in a homeless shelter and I think they're pretty good most areas about getting people out of the cold and making room during cold times. At least the one I was at.
ext_powerout_cope_comments: I can't really think of much. Thankfully, the ones I experienced were resolved quickly without so much as food spoiling. So if it were a longer outage, my answers would be different. I've only experienced hours of power loss.

ext_cold_cope_comments: keep wood for fireplace well stocked, matches in a dry place, an electric heater or two, electric blankets are life saving! and lots of water for coffee and tea, and a generator should the electricity also go out. Fortunately my electricity stayed on during the blizzard. My furnace snuffed out because the snow level covered the intake/outtake vents. Once snow was shoveled away from the vents, and ice and snow unclogged from the vents with a wire BBQ brush, the furnace came back on.
ext_powerout_cope_comments: The power was out for 18 hours. Fortunately I purchased two LED lamps soon after I moved to the mountain as a precaution. Thank heavens for bright LED light! The gas remained on, so matches lit the stove burners, I was able to cook on the stovetop. ext_earthquake_cope_comments: I'm sorry. The earthquake we had about 15 years ago may not have been major, at all. It was scary, though, because it's very, very rare for us to have an earthquake in this area (Baltimore - although the center of the quake was in Virginia,) where you can feel the ground moving under your feet. I was on the ground floor of my workplace - a major university - when it happened, and I went out into the street.  Campus EHS had all sorts of preps for a fire, toxic fumes, etc., but they seemed to have nothing at all in place for an earthquake. Our offices were closed for a day to check the structures for safety. A minor crack appeared in the street I live on, and my house is still settling.
ext_powerout_cope_comments: The Derecho came through here in the summer of 2012 and we were without power for 8 days. My young adult son - who lived with me - and I were very unprepared. It was very hot here. He & I both slept in the living room to keep cooler. I was able to buy a small battery-powered fan or two, but they were quickly selling out. I now have many battery-powered items: fans, lights, clock, a radio, and a good stock of batteries. I also have fuel for my fireplace, should we lose power in the wintertime. I have a lot of non-perishable food and quite a few gallons of water stored. I'm always adding to this, esp. the water.

ext_cold_cope_comments: Not run outdoors!   Seriously, I live in Chicago. While extreme cold is much less common now than it was in the 1970s-1990s, I can recall brutal colds snaps from those years - and was amazed at how well people and institutions functioned.   Were those cold snaps pleasant - of course not. But I went to work, and sometimes DID run outdoors. Yes, we did stay at home more than we would have otherwise, but life did not come to a screeching halt.
ext_powerout_cope_comments: When you speak of coping with a power outage, you fail to mention a crucial factor: the DURATION of the outage. Recent hurricanes have left wide areas int he southeast US without power for days on end.  But here in Chicago, power outages in recent years have become much less frequent due to utility system upgrades.. And they are short - a few hours. I've lived in Chicago since 1969, and the worst power outage I personally experienced was about twenty five years ago. As best I can recall, it lasted <24 hours. All other outages were much shorter - a few hours, just a minor inconvenience. Coping with an outage several days long would be a different story.

ext_powerout_cope_comments: Just experienced a power outage when a bomb-cyclone took out transmission lines and driving 600,000 plus homes and businesses into darkness. My power and cable were out for 6 days. Using a flashlight, I used the daytime house to clean old files. To move my car, I disconnected the handle and raised the door manually. I also ordered an emergency radio to power my laptop and cell phone batteries, along with a Coleman Lantern which provided more light than the flashlight. Before the Amazon purchased arrived, I went to the Redmond Senior and Community Center to charge my devices and to stay warm.
comments: When a bomb-cyclone takes out dozens of 1,000LB transmission lines that need to be delivered by helicopter, there isn't much a community can do, other than to wait until the repairs have been made. ext_heat_cope_comments:
to cope with extreme heat:

Stay Hydrated: Drink plenty of water, avoiding alcohol or caffeine.
Stay Indoors: Limit outdoor activities, especially during peak heat hours.
Use Cooling Devices: Use fans, air conditioning, or cool showers to stay comfortable.
Wear Light Clothing: Opt for loose, light-colored clothes and a hat for sun protection.
Close Curtains: Block out sunlight by closing blinds or curtains to keep your space cool.
Eat Light: Avoid heavy meals and opt for lighter, cooler foods.
Check on Vulnerable People: Monitor elderly, sick, or young children for signs of heat-related illnesses.
Use Sunscreen: If outdoors, apply sunscreen regularly to avoid sunburn.
Staying cool, hydrated, and avoiding heat stress are key to managing extreme heat.
ext_flooding_cope_comments:
o cope with major flooding:

Evacuate if needed and follow local authorities’ instructions.
Stay informed via news or emergency apps.
Secure valuables and move items to higher ground.
Prepare an emergency kit with essentials.
Avoid floodwater and stay safe.
Focus on mental health, staying connected with loved ones.
Assess damage carefully after flooding and contact services for help.
comments:
To better prepare for severe disruptions or extreme events, communities can take several proactive steps:

Emergency Plans: Ensure everyone in the community has a clear emergency plan, including evacuation routes, communication strategies, and designated meeting points.

Local Resources: Strengthen community centers and local resources (shelters, first-aid stations) to support residents during emergencies.

Training & Education: Offer disaster preparedness training for all ages, including basic first aid, CPR, and how to respond in different emergencies like floods, fires, or extreme weather.

Early Warning Systems: Invest in reliable systems for alerting the community about severe weather or disruptions, ensuring everyone has access to these updates.

Infrastructure Resilience: Improve infrastructure to withstand extreme events—such as reinforcing buildings, upgrading power grids, and maintaining clear drainage systems to reduce flood risk.

Mutual Aid Networks: Build community networks for support during tough times. Neighbors helping neighbors is vital, especially for vulnerable populations.

Sustainability: Promote sustainability through energy efficiency, green spaces, and disaster-resistant building practices to reduce long-term impacts.

Preparedness, education, and community solidarity are key to reducing the impacts of extreme events and ensuring a swift recovery.

ext_heat_cope_comments: I would make sure to stay well-hydrated by drinking plenty of water throughout the day. I would wear lightweight, light-colored clothing to help reflect the sun and keep myself cool. I would seek shade whenever possible, especially during the hottest hours of the day. I would take advantage of indoor activities, like watching movies or reading, where the air conditioning would keep me comfortable. I would also make sure to apply sunscreen if I go outside to protect my skin from UV rays. And if I had the chance, I would look for a place with a pool or a beach to cool off and enjoy the water.
ext_cold_cope_comments: I would make sure to wear several layers of clothing to stay warm. A good thermal base layer and a thick jacket would be my best allies. I wouldn't forget gloves, scarves, and hats, as protecting my hands and head is essential to combat the cold. I would prepare teas or hot chocolates that comfort me and help me warm up from the inside. I would also spend time watching movies, reading a good book, or trying new recipes in the kitchen to keep myself busy. If the weather allows, I would go out for a walk to exercise and enjoy the fresh air, even if it's with a thick coat. And when the sun is out, I would step outside to enjoy the natural light, which always boosts my mood.

ext_cold_cope_comments: It depends on what you mean by extreme.  My daughter once lost power and stayed in our house with her kids for several days.  Extreme cold is different depending on where you live. Most people living in Kansas or Michigan would tough it out. 40 degrees in Florida might be different. I wish it were possible for me to have a fireplace.  In the past, I got respite from severe cold (due to power outages in winter) by going to the library, or to the grocery store and running other errands.  Unless weather conditions prevent me from driving, that's what I'll do the next time it happens.  Meanwhile, I make sure to always have candles and canned food at home, no matter what the weather or time of day.
ext_powerout_cope_comments: My neighborhood is not as prone to frequent power outages as it used to be when I first moved here 20 years ago.  But over the years, I've learned to always have candles & matches handy, a mechanical can opener, several battery-powered lanterns/flashlights, and extra blankets, etc.  If it gets too cold for me to function, at least in the day time I am at work, or I can go to the library.  At night, just pile on extra blankets, and sleep through it.
comments: I live on the Tulalip Tribes' reservation, on land that the Tribes lease to me (I own the house).  Residents (both tribal and non-tribal members) are serviced by Tulalip Utilities as well as Snohomish P.U.D., also by both tribal police & fire departments as well as Marysville police. and state patrol police.   In the past, severe storms have made our main route through the rez unpassable by fallen trees and downed power lines.  Unpassable for almost a whole day one time.  It was once cold enough to for Tulalip Bay (salt-water, part of Puget Sound) to completely freeze over for days.  Yet I've never felt unsafe, or unable to get help if I were to need it.  So, no. I don't have any ideas about how to improve safety or service here on the rez, because it is already of utmost importance to those who live here.

ext_cold_cope_comments:
Layer Up: Wearing multiple layers of clothing helps trap heat. Start with a moisture-wicking base layer, add an insulating layer, and finish with a waterproof, windproof outer layer.

Insulate Your Home: Ensure windows and doors are properly sealed. Use heavy curtains, draft stoppers, and consider adding extra insulation to your home.

Stay Hydrated and Eat Well: Drinking plenty of fluids and eating high-energy foods can help your body stay warm.
comments:
Emergency Communication Plan: Ensure there's a reliable way to communicate before, during, and after an emergency. This could include phone trees, social media groups, or even designated meeting spots.

Community Education: Regular workshops or seminars can educate people on how to prepare for various types of emergencies, from natural disasters to man-made events.

Volunteer Training: Create a network of trained volunteers who can assist in emergency response efforts. This could involve first aid training, search and rescue

Create a Cool Zone: If you don't have air conditioning, designate a cool room in your home. Close off vents to other rooms and keep the cool room as shaded as possible.
Utilize Cooling Techniques:
Wet Clothes: Dampen clothing with cool water for evaporative cooling.   
Cool Compresses: Apply cold compresses to your wrists, neck, and forehead.   
Ice Packs: Use ice packs strategically on pulse points.

Stay Calm: Panic can lead to poor decisions. Take deep breaths and focus on protecting yourself.   
Drop, Cover, and Hold On: This is the most important thing to do during an earthquake.
If Outdoors: Move to an open area away from buildings, trees, and power lines.   
If in a Vehicle: Stop the car in a clear area and stay inside until the shaking stops.

ext_heat_cope_comments:
Outdoor Plans:
I'd plan them for early morning or late evening when temperatures are cooler. Bring a friend along for a shaded picnic or a walk.

Create a Cool Sanctuary:
Designate a specific room in my home as my "cool zone." Use fans and hang up light-colored sheets to block out the sun, making it a cozy retreat.

Wardrobe Choices:
Go through my closet to pick favorite lightweight, breathable outfits. Maybe even plan a fun photo shoot in my summer attire to lift your spirits.

Chill-Out Rituals:
Make it a routine to take cool showers or baths at specific times each day, perhaps as a refreshing way to break up your work-from-home schedule.
ext_powerout_cope_comments:
Stay Informed:
by using a battery-powered radio or phone (if charged) to get updates from local news or utility companies.

Safety:
I'll avoid using candles due to fire risks; use flashlights instead.
I'll keep my refrigerator and freezer doors closed to maintain food safety.

Backup Power:
If available, i'll use a generator for essential devices, but ensure it's used outdoors to prevent carbon monoxide poisoning.

Communication:
I would keep my phone charged using a portable charger, and check in with family and friends.

Food and Water:
Use perishable food first and have a supply of non-perishable items.
Store water in clean containers; plan for at least one gallon per person per day.
comments:
Community Emergency Plans:
Encourage local neighborhoods to develop and share comprehensive emergency plans. This could include designated meeting points, communication channels, and resource sharing.

Emergency Kits:
Organize community workshops on assembling emergency kits. Provide lists of essential items, including water, non-perishable food, first aid supplies, and flashlights.

Local Resource Awareness:
Create a community resource map that highlights local shelters, hospitals, and emergency services. Distribute this map through community centers or digital platforms.

Training Programs:
Offer training sessions on first aid, CPR, and basic emergency response. Partner with local organizations or the Red Cross to facilitate these programs.

Neighborhood Watch:
Strengthen neighborhood watch programs to promote safety and communication during emergencies. Encourage regular meetings to discuss safety concerns and preparedness.

Community Communication Network:
Establish a reliable communication network using social media groups or messaging apps to keep residents informed during crises.
